(Starr) My dream at 13
was to play drums.

697
00:49:17,112 --> 00:49:19,342
I started in hospital.

698
00:49:19,414 --> 00:49:24,010
I was in hospital
with tuberculosis for a year,

699
00:49:24,119 --> 00:49:26,314
and so to keep us busy...

700
00:49:26,388 --> 00:49:28,788
I learned to knit.

701
00:49:30,158 --> 00:49:33,559
So they'd give you, like, things to do
'cause we couldn't do a lot.

702
00:49:33,628 --> 00:49:36,426
So then,
every couple of weeks,

703
00:49:36,498 --> 00:49:41,595
a music teacher would come in
with little drums, tambourines, maracas.

704
00:49:41,670 --> 00:49:46,972
I fell in love with the drum. I wouldn't be in
the hospital band unless I got a drum.

705
00:49:47,075 --> 00:49:52,707
Then I came out of hospital and made
my own snare drum out of a biscuit tin

706
00:49:52,781 --> 00:49:55,272
and pieces of firewood as sticks.

707
00:49:55,350 --> 00:49:58,012
I couldn't play, but I could hit.

708
00:49:58,119 --> 00:50:00,952
You know,
and that's how it started.

709
00:50:01,022 --> 00:50:06,551
Now they give me a drum set a week,
you know, if I want one.

710
00:50:06,628 --> 00:50:08,960
It's so hard.
You got nothing, you get nothing.

711
00:50:09,030 --> 00:50:11,760
You got everything,
they'll give you anything.

712
00:50:11,833 --> 00:50:14,666
("A Day in the Life")

713
00:50:19,507 --> 00:50:24,001
I read the news today,
oh, boy

714
00:50:25,880 --> 00:50:30,146
About a lucky man
who made the grade

715
00:50:30,218 --> 00:50:35,918
Well, I think that the show has to have
some gritty or sad moments too,

716
00:50:35,990 --> 00:50:38,481
because that was life.
That is life, you know?

717
00:50:38,593 --> 00:50:43,758
And it can't just be happy-go-lucky
from the beginning to end.

718
00:50:47,135 --> 00:50:52,437
I remember when I went to the Dakota
building and Yoko Ono's apartment

719
00:50:52,507 --> 00:50:54,941
to present
the concept of the show.

720
00:50:55,043 --> 00:51:00,003
And I remember the moment
of John Lennon's murder.

721
00:51:00,115 --> 00:51:04,051
And when I came up there,
I was really, like... (sighs)

722
00:51:04,152 --> 00:51:07,349
I was really shaken

723
00:51:07,422 --> 00:51:11,290
by just being there.

724
00:51:11,393 --> 00:51:15,659
And she offered me a cup of tea.

725
00:51:15,764 --> 00:51:19,063
She told me, "Welcome into this."

726
00:51:19,134 --> 00:51:21,659
Then I just felt more comfortable,

727
00:51:21,736 --> 00:51:26,139
and simply I expressed
what I thought the show should be,

728
00:51:26,241 --> 00:51:32,407
and I left the meeting with
great encouragement and strength.

729
00:51:35,550 --> 00:51:39,611
I read the news today, oh, boy

730
00:51:41,556 --> 00:51:45,253
Julia is the character of a song
on the White Album,

731
00:51:45,360 --> 00:51:47,760
but she is also John Lennon's mother

732
00:51:47,829 --> 00:51:52,926
who was killed by a policeman
driving a car when he was a teenager.

733
00:51:53,034 --> 00:52:00,907
And as you can hear him singing
"Julia" or "Mother" in his solo career,

734
00:52:00,975 --> 00:52:05,969
you can appreciate
how sensitive he was about her.

735
00:52:08,283 --> 00:52:12,720
Then, is it too sensitive to be there
with the blessing of the Beatles?

736
00:52:12,787 --> 00:52:18,589
(Ono) I'm very glad that "Julia"
is something that they're working on.

737
00:52:19,594 --> 00:52:23,530
John had an incredible, incredible
love for his mother.

738
00:52:23,631 --> 00:52:25,929
He was very, very saddened

739
00:52:26,034 --> 00:52:31,301
that his mother never saw him
become so famous.

740
00:52:32,240 --> 00:52:36,074
And that was one thing
that he regretted all the time.

741
00:52:36,144 --> 00:52:38,908
("Julia")

742
00:52:42,984 --> 00:52:46,147
(George Martin) People say,
"What's your favorite song?"

743
00:52:46,221 --> 00:52:48,746
I say, "I don't know -
there were so many of them."

744
00:52:48,823 --> 00:52:53,351
But if I had to pick one of John's it would
probably be "Strawberry Fields Forever".

745
00:52:53,428 --> 00:52:57,262
It's such an extraordinary song.

746
00:52:57,332 --> 00:53:00,426
And the first time I heard it,
we'd been...

747
00:53:00,502 --> 00:53:05,030
Up to that point, we'd been making
albums which we had to rush,

748
00:53:05,106 --> 00:53:08,906
until they made the decision,
wisely and rightly,

749
00:53:08,977 --> 00:53:12,003
not to do any more touring
but to concentrate on recording.

750
00:53:12,113 --> 00:53:15,776
And the very first song
we recorded after that decision

751
00:53:15,850 --> 00:53:18,318
was John's "Strawberry Fields".

752
00:53:18,386 --> 00:53:23,153
As usual, I perched myself
on a high chair, like a bar stool,

753
00:53:23,224 --> 00:53:27,661
and John stood in front of me with his
acoustic guitar and started singing.

754
00:53:28,630 --> 00:53:34,330
No one, I think, is in my tree

755
00:53:35,103 --> 00:53:38,834
And I was knocked out.
I thought, "What an extraordinary song."

756
00:53:38,907 --> 00:53:40,465
"What a beautiful song."

757
00:53:40,542 --> 00:53:45,138
He was a marvelous man,
but he was never really satisfied

758
00:53:45,213 --> 00:53:47,545
with anything he did.

759
00:53:48,483 --> 00:53:51,714
In the year before he died
I spent a night with him,

760
00:53:51,786 --> 00:53:55,051
and we talked about old times.

761
00:53:55,156 --> 00:53:58,489
We had a lovely evening.
Then out of the blue, he said to me:

762
00:53:58,593 --> 00:54:01,357
"You know, George, if I could,

763
00:54:01,429 --> 00:54:05,661
I'd record everything we did again."

764
00:54:05,733 --> 00:54:10,227
I said, "You can't be serious, John.
We did some great stuff."

765
00:54:10,305 --> 00:54:14,173
"What are you on about?"
He said, "We could have done it better."

766
00:54:14,275 --> 00:54:16,368
I said, "What about 'Strawberry Fields'?"

767
00:54:16,477 --> 00:54:20,880
And he looked at me over his glasses and
he said, "Especially 'Strawberry Fields'."

768
00:54:20,949 --> 00:54:26,148
And I thought, "Gosh," you know.
I practically bled for that song.

769
00:54:27,355 --> 00:54:30,916
Nothing is real

770
00:54:30,992 --> 00:54:34,792
And nothing to get hung about

771
00:54:34,862 --> 00:54:38,263
(Giles Martin) After we did it
using the different versions,

772
00:54:38,333 --> 00:54:40,858
Yoko said it was nothing
to do with the music at all,

773
00:54:40,935 --> 00:54:44,735
it was that he didn't like his voice on it,
he didn't like his singing on it.

774
00:54:44,839 --> 00:54:48,866
He had a great voice and yet he was
always asking me to distort it:

775
00:54:48,943 --> 00:54:51,537
"Put more tape echo on it.
I can't bear that."

776
00:54:51,613 --> 00:54:58,177
I think that also John had this vision
in his mind which was a fantastic sound

777
00:54:58,252 --> 00:55:00,117
and he wanted it to be realized.

778
00:55:00,188 --> 00:55:02,179
But he was never very practical.

779
00:55:02,256 --> 00:55:08,559
He would talk to me in
terms of colors and so on, and dreams.

780
00:55:08,630 --> 00:55:12,498
And I had to pin him down, saying,
"OK, what instrument do you use?"

781
00:55:12,600 --> 00:55:14,591
"How do we get this off the ground?"

782
00:55:14,669 --> 00:55:16,603
He didn't want
to be bothered with that.

783
00:55:16,671 --> 00:55:19,834
He wanted to create something
that would just flow.

784
00:55:19,907 --> 00:55:21,875
("Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds")

785
00:55:21,943 --> 00:55:24,104
(man) Le prochain.

786
00:55:26,347 --> 00:55:29,145
Regarde ta boule.

787
