1167
01:26:49,656 --> 01:26:53,285
(Paul McCartney) We'd said to them,
"Be as experimental as you can."

1168
01:26:53,360 --> 01:26:56,761
And so they gave us
this little demo playback.

1169
01:26:56,830 --> 01:27:01,460
And suddenly they'd taken
"Within You Without You"

1170
01:27:01,535 --> 01:27:04,095
and put the "Tomorrow Never Knows"
drums on it,

1171
01:27:04,171 --> 01:27:08,130
and then started to bring in a guitar
from here and a thing from there.

1172
01:27:08,208 --> 01:27:12,872
And we went, "That's it exactly.
That's what we're talking about."

1173
01:27:12,946 --> 01:27:16,143
And I think we were all amazed
at how well it worked.

1174
01:27:17,251 --> 01:27:19,412
I'll bring in the song gradually.

1175
01:27:19,486 --> 01:27:23,445
("Tomorrow Never Knows" intro)

1176
01:27:23,524 --> 01:27:26,823
(segues into "Within You Without You")

1177
01:27:32,900 --> 01:27:35,664
If I take down "Tomorrow" now...

1178
01:27:38,438 --> 01:27:43,102
(Yoko Ono) George Martin and Giles
Martin did justice to The Beatles' music.

1179
01:27:43,177 --> 01:27:46,840
And not only that,
but I think they went a step further.

1180
01:27:46,914 --> 01:27:51,613
This is showing
that the music is so strong,

1181
01:27:51,685 --> 01:27:55,177
an incredible artistic power that it has,

1182
01:27:55,255 --> 01:27:59,419
that it can be used in a different way.

1183
01:27:59,493 --> 01:28:03,122
(Giles) You're playing with what
everyone holds so precious and dear.

1184
01:28:03,197 --> 01:28:08,863
They heard it and loved it. They loved
the idea of not doing something ordinary.

1185
01:28:08,936 --> 01:28:13,032
And The Beatles never, never did
anything ordinary.

1186
01:28:17,578 --> 01:28:21,844
(George) "Tomorrow Never Knows"
has got a great rhythm sound to it.

1187
01:28:21,915 --> 01:28:24,975
Ringo's drums are very hypnotic.

1188
01:28:25,052 --> 01:28:29,386
And, of course, "Within You Without You"
is a well-known George song.

1189
01:28:29,456 --> 01:28:31,981
It was a matter of fitting, really,

1190
01:28:32,059 --> 01:28:36,086
because there are moments when
you have to stop it, then start again.

1191
01:28:36,163 --> 01:28:40,224
You have to work with the original rhythm
and tabla sound, and so on.

1192
01:28:42,669 --> 01:28:49,165
I think George's love of those sounds
of Indian instruments was so prescient.

1193
01:28:49,243 --> 01:28:52,303
They're timeless instruments
and he always knew that.

1194
01:28:52,379 --> 01:28:55,109
That's why he loved them
and he loved to use them.

1195
01:28:55,182 --> 01:29:03,351
But it's amazing that today they actually
add some kind of edge to the music.

1196
01:29:03,423 --> 01:29:05,584
(Giles) The Beatles recorded in a very...

1197
01:29:05,659 --> 01:29:10,494
My father was economical - he always
says this - with how things were done.

1198
01:29:10,564 --> 01:29:13,624
People go,
"You could use the drums from Help!"

1199
01:29:13,700 --> 01:29:19,400
You go, "No, I can't. They're with the
guitars and the bass." That's a challenge.

1200
01:29:19,473 --> 01:29:23,375
People go, "Why didn't you use this?"
But they're tied together.

1201
01:29:23,443 --> 01:29:30,110
Turn off your mind, relax
and float downstream

1202
01:29:33,654 --> 01:29:37,454
It is not dying

1203
01:29:39,092 --> 01:29:42,892
It is not dying

1204
01:29:48,001 --> 01:29:52,995
There's so much space in what they did.
Suddenly the tablas had more importance

1205
01:29:53,073 --> 01:29:59,410
and the different instruments
just flying around the room.

1206
01:29:59,479 --> 01:30:02,971
I think that was the one
that really sold everybody on it.

1207
01:30:03,050 --> 01:30:08,682
Life flows on
within you and without you...

1208
01:30:16,697 --> 01:30:21,100
Ringo and Paul were constantly saying,
"Go as far as you can."

1209
01:30:21,168 --> 01:30:23,693
"We will stop you. Go as far as you can."

1210
01:30:23,770 --> 01:30:27,797
But there's only so far you can go before
you start completely losing your mind.

1211
01:30:29,009 --> 01:30:30,067
And "Octopus's Garden"...

1212
01:30:30,143 --> 01:30:35,137
I had an idea to put Ringo on his own,
you know, because it's such a...

1213
01:30:35,215 --> 01:30:38,275
To leave his vocal kind of bare.

1214
01:30:38,352 --> 01:30:41,879
(George) We wanted to use
one of Ringo's tracks,

1215
01:30:41,955 --> 01:30:46,688
and the show director was very keen
on using "Octopus's Garden".

1216
01:30:46,760 --> 01:30:51,629
We started off with a very orchestral
and dreamy beginning,

1217
01:30:51,698 --> 01:30:56,397
and most people who listened to it
said, "Where did that come from?"

1218
01:30:56,470 --> 01:30:58,904
"That doesn't sound like Beatles to me."

1219
01:30:58,972 --> 01:31:02,499
Well, of course, it was Beatles
and it was something I had scored.

1220
01:31:02,576 --> 01:31:06,774
And we cut up Ringo's voice,

1221
01:31:06,847 --> 01:31:10,681
so that instead of singing the track as it is,

1222
01:31:10,751 --> 01:31:13,618
he does it quite slowly and leisurely
to begin with.

1223
01:31:15,322 --> 01:31:17,654
(Ringo) I'd like to be

1224
01:31:18,892 --> 01:31:21,725
Under the sea

1225
01:31:21,795 --> 01:31:25,629
In an octopus's garden

1226
01:31:25,699 --> 01:31:27,291
In the shade

1227
01:31:30,003 --> 01:31:33,769
- He'd let us in
- ("Yellow Submarine" starts)

1228
01:31:33,840 --> 01:31:36,001
Knows where we've been

1229
01:31:36,810 --> 01:31:39,779
In his octopus's garden

1230
01:31:40,714 --> 01:31:42,944
In the shade

1231
01:31:48,755 --> 01:31:52,987
I'd ask my friends to come and see...

1232
01:31:53,060 --> 01:31:55,551
(Giles) Ringo was dead interested in this.

1233
01:31:55,629 --> 01:32:00,066
He'd come in, and I worked in order,
so "Octopus's Garden" hadn't been done.

1234
01:32:00,133 --> 01:32:03,569
He kept saying, "How about
'Octopus's Garden'? You done it yet?"

1235
01:32:03,637 --> 01:32:06,231
He'd come in, and I'd go, "No."

1236
01:32:06,306 --> 01:32:11,710
And so there was this pressure
mounting up. "You go mad on it. Go mad."

1237
01:32:11,778 --> 01:32:16,613
"Don't, you know... Don't skimp
on my song!" It was one of those things.

1238
01:32:16,683 --> 01:32:18,310
And I'm thinking, "Oh, OK."

1239
01:32:18,385 --> 01:32:21,218
So originally I tried
the end of "Glass Onion".

1240
01:32:22,022 --> 01:32:25,458
I put that with his vocal and
actually it sounded too dark and eerie.

1241
01:32:25,525 --> 01:32:30,428
I wanted him on his own - Ringo on
his own - 'cause he's such a character.

1242
01:32:30,497 --> 01:32:34,593
Then I took the strings from "Good Night",
put them up a tone

1243
01:32:34,668 --> 01:32:37,364
and changed the key slightly.

1244
01:32:37,437 --> 01:32:40,406
And, it's funny, it just fitted.

1245
01:32:40,474 --> 01:32:44,069
And I did the whole of "Good Night",
and my dad came in and goes:

1246
01:32:44,144 --> 01:32:48,274
"What are you doing?" I said, "Well,
I thought this might be kind of cool."

1247
01:32:48,348 --> 01:32:53,285
He goes, "Oh, my God!"
He goes - and this was good direction -

1248
01:32:53,353 --> 01:32:57,915
he goes, "But you should
just chop the first verse back in again."

1249
01:32:57,991 --> 01:33:01,825
"Don't play the whole thing."
So there's a bit of a clash going on.

1250
01:33:01,895 --> 01:33:06,798
- The rhythm track to "Octopus's Garden".
- ("Octopus's Garden" plays)

1251
01:33:09,436 --> 01:33:14,169
- It's just very light. And so...
- That's the original?

1252
01:33:14,241 --> 01:33:17,335
That's the original.
So we combined "Lovely Rita".

1253
01:33:17,410 --> 01:33:19,071
(drumbeat)

1254
01:33:19,146 --> 01:33:21,205
Yeah.

1255
01:33:21,281 --> 01:33:23,977
And it's the same groove
'cause it's just Ringo.

1256
01:33:24,050 --> 01:33:27,349
We didn't sample or move anything.

1257
01:33:27,420 --> 01:33:32,448
And he's exactly right, too.
It has to be right on the nose.

1258
01:33:33,360 --> 01:33:35,988
(Ringo) I'd like to be

1259
01:33:36,062 --> 01:33:38,360
Under the sea...

1260
01:33:39,032 --> 01:33:43,093
(Giles) Because you wanted
the double time in this section here,

1261
01:33:43,170 --> 01:33:45,195
in comes "Polythene Pam".

1262
01:33:45,272 --> 01:33:49,208
(percussion on "Polythene Pam")

1263
01:33:51,478 --> 01:33:54,276
(segues into "Helter Skelter")

1264
01:33:55,849 --> 01:34:00,343
The end goes into "Helter Skelter" - the
guitars and rhythm are "Helter Skelter".

1265
01:34:00,420 --> 01:34:04,083
So I really threw in the kitchen sink.
It finished off with "Sun King".

1266
01:34:04,157 --> 01:34:07,251
I threw everything at that song,
to make Ringo happy.

1267
01:34:07,327 --> 01:34:10,319
I was so nervous when he came.
He knocked on the door

1268
01:34:10,397 --> 01:34:13,662
and opened the door to my studio -
a lot like this one at Abbey Road.

1269
01:34:13,733 --> 01:34:15,894
I played it and I stood in the corner.

1270
01:34:15,969 --> 01:34:21,407
First of all, I thought he had
my voice a little too loud.

1271
01:34:21,474 --> 01:34:25,843
I always tried to hide it a bit.
But it works 'cause it's very pure.

1272
01:34:27,047 --> 01:34:29,379
(Ringo) I'd like to be

1273
01:34:30,483 --> 01:34:32,144
Under the sea...

1274
01:34:32,219 --> 01:34:35,347
When he heard the strings of
"Good Night", his face dropped -

1275
01:34:35,422 --> 01:34:38,482
he's not that keen on his vocal
on "Good Night" apparently,

1276
01:34:38,558 --> 01:34:42,824
so he was delighted
that it didn't happen, and he loved it.

1277
01:34:44,598 --> 01:34:48,534
In an octopus's garden with you

1278
01:34:49,736 --> 01:34:53,263
In an octopus's garden with you

1279
01:35:03,283 --> 01:35:05,945
(intro of "Lady Madonna")

1280
01:35:10,323 --> 01:35:13,190
(Giles) The Beatles did
a lot of amazing psychedelic stuff,

1281
01:35:13,260 --> 01:35:15,990
really heartfelt stuff
and a lot of rock stuff.

1282
01:35:16,062 --> 01:35:20,362
But "Lady Madonna" is slightly more,
I suppose, funky in a way.

1283
01:35:20,433 --> 01:35:25,735
So we got the track up
and I listened to it on four-track.

1284
01:35:25,805 --> 01:35:30,936
What we do is listen to each four-track.
They bounced, so we put them together.

1285
01:35:31,011 --> 01:35:35,072
The first track you hear
when you get it out is this.

1286
01:35:35,148 --> 01:35:37,878
(piano solo on "Lady Madonna")

1287
01:35:43,657 --> 01:35:46,285
- Yeah.
- Which is...

1288
01:35:46,359 --> 01:35:49,522
- I think it's almost boogie-woogie.
- Yeah. It's great.

1289
01:35:49,596 --> 01:35:52,724
And then on top of that, they put this:

1290
01:35:52,799 --> 01:35:57,031
(drum and bass play
on a different channel)

1291
01:35:57,103 --> 01:36:00,504
Obviously listening to themselves
in the cans.

1292
01:36:02,642 --> 01:36:05,543
- If you put them both together...
- (complete version)

1293
01:36:05,612 --> 01:36:09,708
On "Lady Madonna" we departed
from our normal procedure,

1294
01:36:09,783 --> 01:36:14,186
because normally we would lay down
a rhythm track and overdub things on it.

1295
01:36:14,254 --> 01:36:19,282
But this song was piano-driven, really -
Paul on his piano, working away.

1296
01:36:19,359 --> 01:36:22,055
The bass and other things
were added later,

1297
01:36:22,128 --> 01:36:24,460
which was not what we normally did.

1298
01:36:24,531 --> 01:36:28,991
See how they run

1299
01:36:29,069 --> 01:36:33,028
Lady Madonna,
baby at your breast...

1300
01:36:33,106 --> 01:36:37,600
You know, when The Beatles started,
none of them played keyboards at all.

1301
01:36:37,677 --> 01:36:44,549
And when they were successful, I think
Paul got himself a piano first, John later.

1302
01:36:44,617 --> 01:36:50,817
And yet in a very short space of time Paul
became extremely good at playing piano.

1303
01:36:50,890 --> 01:36:53,450
And on "Lady Madonna"
he plays a brilliant piano.

1304
01:36:58,565 --> 01:37:02,797
Lady Madonna,
children at your feet,

1305
01:37:02,869 --> 01:37:07,465
Wonder how you manage
to make ends meet...

1306
01:37:07,540 --> 01:37:10,668
(Giles) I didn't realize that
Paul wrote "Lady Madonna",

1307
01:37:10,744 --> 01:37:13,212
then John wrote "Hey Bulldog"
to compete with it.

1308
01:37:13,279 --> 01:37:16,248
I had no idea
there was this thing going on.

1309
01:37:16,316 --> 01:37:20,810
They're both great piano parts and
it's funny how they just work together.

1310
01:37:21,354 --> 01:37:24,346
So "Bulldog" on its own, which is:

1311
01:37:25,959 --> 01:37:28,928
(instrumental section of "Hey Bulldog")

1312
01:37:31,231 --> 01:37:35,725
I always wanted to get "Hey Bulldog"
in the show 'cause it's such a fantastic riff.

1313
01:37:35,802 --> 01:37:37,702
So put some other tracks in.

1314
01:37:37,771 --> 01:37:41,730
I got it to work in the solo section, and
I thought what would work over the top

1315
01:37:41,808 --> 01:37:46,336
and found that Eric Clapton's guitar solo
from "While My Guitar Gently Weeps"

1316
01:37:46,413 --> 01:37:51,476
complemented it nicely and it just worked.
It took a while to get it all to work.

1317
01:37:51,551 --> 01:37:57,353
I used the organ from "I Want You
(She's So Heavy)" to glue it together.

1318
01:37:57,424 --> 01:38:00,825
(guitar solo
together with "Hey Bulldog")

1319
01:38:00,894 --> 01:38:03,988
- And you hear it sped up.
- (fast-paced guitar)

1320
01:38:04,063 --> 01:38:06,361
Billy Preston was very good but...

1321
01:38:14,240 --> 01:38:18,040
There's the "Lady Madonna" vocals...
and the guitar coming in.

1322
01:38:18,111 --> 01:38:21,308
And then back into "Lady Madonna".

1323
01:38:21,381 --> 01:38:24,782
(George) Yeah. It's mixed together nicely.

1324
01:38:25,785 --> 01:38:30,620
(McCartney) You finally hear Ronnie Scott.
The sax player in the middle is Ronnie.

1325
01:38:30,690 --> 01:38:36,253
I knew Ronnie, so I said to him, "Would
you work on this record we're making?"

1326
01:38:36,329 --> 01:38:41,164
"We just need a nice wild... (imitates sax)
Sax solo. You can do that, Ronnie."

1327
01:38:41,234 --> 01:38:43,429
He said, "Yeah, mate, I'll do that."

1328
01:38:43,503 --> 01:38:49,203
So he came along to the session,
played it great, but in the mix we buried it.

1329
01:38:49,275 --> 01:38:53,541
I met up with him weeks later after and
he'd heard it on the radio or somewhere.

1330
01:38:53,613 --> 01:38:58,050
He said, "What did you do to my solo?"
I said, "Sorry, Ronnie. It's pop."

1331
01:38:58,117 --> 01:39:02,247
"This isn't jazz. It's a different thing.
It still sounds good, Ron, great."

1332
01:39:02,322 --> 01:39:05,450
But he was always a bit pissed at...
you know. "What are you doing?"

1333
01:39:05,525 --> 01:39:08,551
So now finally in the show,
at the end of "Lady Madonna",

1334
01:39:08,628 --> 01:39:11,096
you suddenly hear... (imitates sax)

1335
01:39:11,164 --> 01:39:13,155
So he's not with us anymore,

1336
01:39:13,233 --> 01:39:17,795
but he would have been pleased
to finally be revealed in all his glory.

1337
01:39:18,171 --> 01:39:20,503
(sax solo)

1338
01:39:21,341 --> 01:39:23,172
(applause and cheering)

1339
01:39:24,844 --> 01:39:27,335
("Strawberry Fields")

1340
01:39:34,687 --> 01:39:39,215
Let me take you down
'cause I'm going to...

1341
01:39:39,292 --> 01:39:43,092
(George) "Strawberry Fields",
I thought, would be difficult to handle

1342
01:39:43,162 --> 01:39:49,965
because it's one of my favorite tracks
and it's also a kind of icon too.

1343
01:39:50,036 --> 01:39:53,233
It's something which
many people would say:

1344
01:39:53,306 --> 01:39:56,469
"Don't ever touch it.
That is sacrosanct."

1345
01:39:58,545 --> 01:40:03,847
No one I think is in my tree...

1346
01:40:03,917 --> 01:40:07,512
(Giles) Yoko had some tapes from home,
from John's house,

1347
01:40:07,587 --> 01:40:10,215
with him doing early versions of
"Strawberry Fields".

1348
01:40:10,290 --> 01:40:11,985
(George) No one had heard this bit.

1349
01:40:13,960 --> 01:40:15,951
So this is him at home.

1350
01:40:18,364 --> 01:40:23,529
(Lennon) No one I think is in my tree...

1351
01:40:23,603 --> 01:40:27,437
(Giles) So what we did is we took
all of the versions we could find

1352
01:40:27,507 --> 01:40:31,102
and tried to combine them
in one long, expansive song

1353
01:40:31,177 --> 01:40:35,011
that just starts off at home
and finishes in the studio.

1354
01:40:35,081 --> 01:40:38,608
That is I think it's not too bad...

1355
01:40:38,685 --> 01:40:42,815
And while I swanned around,
you tuned all of the...

1356
01:40:42,889 --> 01:40:47,189
You pitch-shifted on the tape machine,
like in the old days, all the versions

1357
01:40:47,260 --> 01:40:49,194
so they're all in the same key.

1358
01:40:49,262 --> 01:40:53,722
(George) It was near enough, but not
near enough for what we were doing.

1359
01:40:54,400 --> 01:40:59,702
Living is easy with eyes closed

1360
01:40:59,772 --> 01:41:03,765
Misunderstanding all you see...

1361
01:41:03,843 --> 01:41:07,745
(Yoko) This show has to be something -
especially John's songs -

1362
01:41:07,814 --> 01:41:10,612
had to be something
that John would be proud of.

1363
01:41:10,683 --> 01:41:18,783
That was my concern, in the sense that
the spirit of the songs will come out well.

1364
01:41:18,858 --> 01:41:21,190
Nothing is real

1365
01:41:22,095 --> 01:41:25,087
And nothing to get hung about

1366
01:41:26,099 --> 01:41:29,125
Strawberry fields forever...

1367
01:41:35,041 --> 01:41:41,071
So now this is the final version -
the final four-track that was done.

1368
01:41:42,915 --> 01:41:46,874
I think I know I mean yes,
but it's all wrong

1369
01:41:46,953 --> 01:41:50,787
(George) Which is like the master, so...

1370
01:41:50,857 --> 01:41:53,451
(end of "Strawberry Fields")

1371
01:41:56,062 --> 01:41:58,690
(Giles) So we used this drumbeat
as a foundation

1372
01:41:58,765 --> 01:42:02,826
'cause the song was faded in and out,
and we still used everything that's there.

1373
01:42:02,902 --> 01:42:07,134
They faded in and out because, of course,
in those days we had no click tracks

1374
01:42:07,206 --> 01:42:09,436
to keep us in synch.

1375
01:42:09,509 --> 01:42:14,173
And, in fact, the rhythm went
completely haywire at one point.

1376
01:42:14,247 --> 01:42:16,681
But there was a bit after it
I wanted to include.

1377
01:42:16,749 --> 01:42:20,446
I couldn't edit them together,
so the only thing I did on the mix

1378
01:42:20,520 --> 01:42:25,355
was to dip them down to nothing,
with the bit that was wobbly,

1379
01:42:25,425 --> 01:42:27,086
then bring them back again.

1380
01:42:27,160 --> 01:42:31,028
So everybody said, "Great idea -
fading, then coming back."

1381
01:42:31,097 --> 01:42:35,466
I didn't tell them the reason,
but now we don't need to do that.

1382
01:42:35,535 --> 01:42:39,335
(instrumental section
of "Strawberry Fields")

1383
01:42:44,110 --> 01:42:47,341
We should run through
the separate elements,

1384
01:42:47,413 --> 01:42:51,975
and the first thing we hear
is "Hey Bulldog", very quietly.

1385
01:42:52,719 --> 01:42:56,621
- And "In My Life".
- (piano solo on "In My Life")

1386
01:42:56,689 --> 01:42:59,852
- And "Penny Lane".
- (trumpet solo on "Penny Lane")

1387
01:43:02,328 --> 01:43:04,489
All happening with the...

1388
01:43:07,533 --> 01:43:09,524
And "Piggies" comes in.

1389
01:43:15,908 --> 01:43:22,279
Meanwhile, we have the whole rhythm
from "Strawberry Fields" at the end.

1390
01:43:24,684 --> 01:43:26,743
And "Hello Goodbye".

1391
01:43:27,820 --> 01:43:33,258
Hela, heba, helloa...

1392
01:43:33,326 --> 01:43:36,818
I think, because The Beatles
had so many musical ideas,

1393
01:43:36,896 --> 01:43:38,955
that often they work together.

1394
01:43:39,031 --> 01:43:44,025
They're so sort of melodic
in what they did, that it's amazing how...

1395
01:43:44,103 --> 01:43:48,039
It's the same brain,
it's just wedged together.

1396
01:43:48,107 --> 01:43:51,873
(Yoko) There's no other Beatles
in the world. It's one and only.

1397
01:43:51,944 --> 01:43:54,879
The Beatles were like
acrobatics of the mind,

1398
01:43:54,947 --> 01:43:58,940
and Cirque du Soleil
is the acrobatics of the body.

1399
01:43:59,018 --> 01:44:01,384
And so when it comes together,

1400
01:44:01,454 --> 01:44:06,551
it makes a kind of... something
that's whole. I like that, yeah.

1401
01:44:06,626 --> 01:44:09,220
("Baby, You Can Drive My Car")

1402
01:44:10,897 --> 01:44:14,697
Asked a girl
what she wanted to be

1403
01:44:14,767 --> 01:44:17,634
She said, baby, can't you see...

1404
01:44:17,703 --> 01:44:19,728
(Giles) No one has done this before.

1405
01:44:19,806 --> 01:44:24,800
No one has gone to their own library
and used themselves.

1406
01:44:24,877 --> 01:44:28,244
It's great The Beatles have done this first.
Others will do it,

1407
01:44:28,314 --> 01:44:31,943
and I hope people like the results
that have come from it.

1408
01:44:32,018 --> 01:44:36,011
(McCartney) There will be people who are
purist and want to hear it as it was.

1409
01:44:36,088 --> 01:44:38,818
And you know what? It exists as it was.

1410
01:44:38,891 --> 01:44:41,860
So, you know, just play your vinyl.

1411
01:44:41,928 --> 01:44:46,297
And I think that's great.
That is how it was.

1412
01:44:46,365 --> 01:44:49,027
But obviously,
by allowing it to happen,

1413
01:44:49,101 --> 01:44:52,366
we don't have a problem
with the remix aspect.

1414
01:44:53,506 --> 01:44:58,307
(George) We're talking about probably
the most important popular music

1415
01:44:58,377 --> 01:45:00,277
of the 20th century,

1416
01:45:00,346 --> 01:45:03,179
and it's historic what we're dealing with.

1417
01:45:03,249 --> 01:45:08,380
Of course, over a period of 90 minutes
we can get in a lot of songs

1418
01:45:08,454 --> 01:45:11,617
which are icons,
which are wonderful.

1419
01:45:11,691 --> 01:45:14,819
And when you hear them in a big room

1420
01:45:14,894 --> 01:45:19,991
with what we've been able to do with them
in surround sound,

1421
01:45:20,066 --> 01:45:22,830
I think you'll have a few shivers
going down your spine.

1422
01:46:19,546 --> 01:46:22,538
("Being For The Benefit Of Mr. Kite")

1423
01:46:25,619 --> 01:46:30,249
Yeah, it's great.
I think that Lennon's voice all over,

1424
01:46:30,323 --> 01:46:33,292
- it sounds very good.
- (George) You're happy with it?

1425
01:46:33,360 --> 01:46:34,850
Yeah. What about you?

1426
01:46:34,928 --> 01:46:38,955
I'd like to be able to hear the voice nearer,
without being louder.

1427
01:46:39,032 --> 01:46:43,264
We can certainly play with that,
see if we can, without increasing the level,

1428
01:46:43,336 --> 01:46:46,999
bring it closer by using the center
speakers on the back of the chair.

1429
01:46:47,074 --> 01:46:52,341
When we did the 5.1, I think
we put a slight slap on him as well,

1430
01:46:52,412 --> 01:46:56,371
and that may just make him boom
a bit more.

1431
01:46:56,450 --> 01:46:59,851
He doesn't sound like he's a ringmaster.

1432
01:47:01,088 --> 01:47:06,287
I fear, with the experience, people thinking
The Beatles are selling out to Las Vegas.

1433
01:47:06,359 --> 01:47:10,659
I think Las Vegas...
There's a lot of money in Las Vegas!

1434
01:47:10,730 --> 01:47:14,359
You can do things in Las Vegas
you can't do anywhere else in the world.

1435
01:47:14,434 --> 01:47:18,370
Even The Beatles couldn't build
a $100m theater

1436
01:47:18,438 --> 01:47:20,065
to put their music into

1437
01:47:20,140 --> 01:47:22,540
which has 6,000 speakers inside.

1438
01:47:22,609 --> 01:47:25,737
- So each section has its own sound?
- Its own sound, yeah.

1439
01:47:25,812 --> 01:47:27,905
You get a little spill from...

1440
01:47:27,981 --> 01:47:33,044
The idea of working with The Beatles'
music is something that is unbelievable.

1441
01:47:33,120 --> 01:47:36,453
It's unbelievable because I grew up...

1442
01:47:36,523 --> 01:47:41,119
That generation was my generation,
and I know The Beatles' music inside out.

1443
01:47:41,194 --> 01:47:45,790
So the idea of working with
The Beatles' music is just fantastic.

1444
01:47:45,866 --> 01:47:49,927
("La Marseillaise" opening
of "All You Need Is Love")

1445
01:47:54,107 --> 01:47:57,270
Love, love, love

1446
01:47:58,512 --> 01:48:01,413
Love, love, love...

1447
01:48:01,481 --> 01:48:05,383
(Deans) We started as a proscenium
theater, then it went to a 360 theater.

1448
01:48:05,452 --> 01:48:09,286
So now the whole auditorium
was around the stage,

1449
01:48:09,356 --> 01:48:13,793
which for me, as a sound designer,
it's like: Where do you put the speakers?

1450
01:48:15,128 --> 01:48:20,156
(Giles) There's left and right,
as you have at home - The Beatles stereo.

1451
01:48:20,233 --> 01:48:23,600
Then we have a speaker in the seat -
we can have this voice up close.

1452
01:48:23,670 --> 01:48:25,763
We have a speaker 80 feet away.

1453
01:48:25,839 --> 01:48:28,137
You can have strings or you can have...

1454
01:48:28,208 --> 01:48:31,075
We have speakers in the ears -
they're three inches away.

1455
01:48:31,144 --> 01:48:37,344
So my idea is to almost feel like you're
dropping someone into a Beatles studio

1456
01:48:37,417 --> 01:48:40,716
where they're
surrounding you completely.

1457
01:48:40,787 --> 01:48:45,349
- So I'll hear these two and this?
- Plus you'll hear...

1458
01:48:45,425 --> 01:48:47,916
The subs for these are in the ceiling.

1459
01:48:47,994 --> 01:48:52,863
And then you have what's behind, like
what we saw downstairs, what's behind,

1460
01:48:52,933 --> 01:48:57,336
what's in front and then the main PA
as well. And then we can move sound...

1461
01:48:57,404 --> 01:49:01,306
- I can't hear a word, mate! Sorry.
- ("Hey Jude" plays loudly)

1462
01:49:01,374 --> 01:49:04,832
(all laugh as McCartney mouths words)

1463
01:49:07,814 --> 01:49:12,717
(Deans) The kind of work I do,
I like for the audience to be enveloped.

1464
01:49:12,786 --> 01:49:17,382
I like for the audience
to be a part of the show.

1465
01:49:17,457 --> 01:49:21,416
And I'm not trying to do it so people go,
"Oh, there's sound around me."

1466
01:49:21,494 --> 01:49:27,194
It should just belong. It should be
as one unified joint production.

1467
01:49:27,267 --> 01:49:30,293
("Hey Jude" carries on playing)

1468
01:49:30,370 --> 01:49:34,204
- I know this song. Yeah.
- Takes a little time, but...

1469
01:49:34,274 --> 01:49:37,243
- Good singer. Who's this?
- We're trying to find out.

1470
01:49:37,310 --> 01:49:39,301
- French guy?
- Yeah!

1471
01:49:39,379 --> 01:49:40,539
Thought so.

1472
01:49:40,614 --> 01:49:43,242
OK, let's move on.

1473
01:49:43,316 --> 01:49:47,685
("La Marseillaise" opening
of "All You Need Is Love")

1474
01:49:47,754 --> 01:49:49,745
Here we go!

1475
01:49:51,591 --> 01:49:54,788
Love, love, love...

1476
01:49:54,861 --> 01:49:58,820
(Giles) I've seen a lot of shows in Vegas
and they sound very good,

1477
01:49:58,898 --> 01:50:02,891
but they don't sound... English!

1478
01:50:04,404 --> 01:50:07,032
I don't mean that in a nasty way at all -
it's great -

1479
01:50:07,107 --> 01:50:09,871
but I think The Beatles
should sound like The Beatles.

1480
01:50:11,344 --> 01:50:14,472
Me and Paul are pretty good
at getting that done.

1481
01:50:14,547 --> 01:50:18,677
Paul Hicks is... Funnily enough,
he's Tony Hicks' son from The Hollies.

1482
01:50:18,752 --> 01:50:20,743
There was a band called The Hollies.

1483
01:50:20,820 --> 01:50:25,917
I've only worked with "son-ofs" - that's the
most important thing: "Who's your dad?"

1484
01:50:25,992 --> 01:50:31,430
He's been at Abbey Road for a long time,
so we'll be here mixing in the theater.

1485
01:50:31,498 --> 01:50:36,367
- I was going backwards and forwards.
- There's too much sub going on.

1486
01:50:36,436 --> 01:50:38,927
(George) Cirque du Soleil
has never had a show

1487
01:50:39,005 --> 01:50:43,135
where the music has been
entirely on tape or on recording.

1488
01:50:43,209 --> 01:50:45,643
They've always had live musicians.

1489
01:50:45,712 --> 01:50:50,775
And they were scared, because
what happens if something goes wrong?

1490
01:50:50,850 --> 01:50:54,911
You know, if a guy hurts himself
and we have to fill in time.

1491
01:50:54,988 --> 01:50:59,721
So we've had to make our music
continuous,

1492
01:50:59,793 --> 01:51:04,127
but, at the same time,
we've had to have flexibility within it.

1493
01:51:04,197 --> 01:51:09,032
There are a lot of places where
you can stretch the music a little bit.

1494
01:51:09,102 --> 01:51:12,765
Or, if it comes to really dire straits,

1495
01:51:12,839 --> 01:51:19,267
then the operator will be able to loop
a particular section and keep it going.

1496
01:51:19,346 --> 01:51:22,679
("Help!" comes to an end)

1497
01:51:25,218 --> 01:51:27,880
(man) On normal Cirque shows -
other Cirque shows -

1498
01:51:27,954 --> 01:51:31,822
the music is written
in the creative process of the show itself.

1499
01:51:31,891 --> 01:51:35,759
And so that way the music
is also eligible to be changed

1500
01:51:35,829 --> 01:51:38,320
over the course of the show
from minute to minute.

1501
01:51:38,398 --> 01:51:42,994
Here, once a song starts
that the whole audience knows,

1502
01:51:43,069 --> 01:51:48,006
you don't want to mess with it,
and we don't want to mess with it either.

1503
01:51:49,008 --> 01:51:50,999
("Here Comes The Sun")

1504
01:51:51,077 --> 01:51:52,738
Little darling

1505
01:51:52,812 --> 01:51:56,873
It's been a long, cold, lonely winter

1506
01:51:58,451 --> 01:51:59,440
Little darling...

1507
01:51:59,519 --> 01:52:02,818
(George) We're playing back
in 5.1 surround,

1508
01:52:02,889 --> 01:52:07,053
which is quite a different experience
to stereo or mono.

1509
01:52:07,127 --> 01:52:09,459
I love it. I think it's great.

1510
01:52:09,529 --> 01:52:13,522
And it gives you another dimension
to the music.

1511
01:52:15,969 --> 01:52:20,406
Hela, heba, helloa...

1512
01:52:20,473 --> 01:52:23,806
(Whiteley) Because so many
of the songs stay the same,

1513
01:52:23,877 --> 01:52:27,438
projections are heavily synchronized
to the music.

1514
01:52:27,514 --> 01:52:30,005
Lighting punches
happen at the exact same time,

1515
01:52:30,083 --> 01:52:35,419
so, from here, we're spitting out numbers
those departments can synchronize too.

1516
01:52:35,488 --> 01:52:37,479
We've done a lot of preparation.

1517
01:52:37,557 --> 01:52:41,550
There's no other Cirque show
with so many elements so tied together

1518
01:52:41,628 --> 01:52:44,563
because they've never had
the music established

1519
01:52:44,631 --> 01:52:47,361
40 years before the show was created,
like this one.

1520
01:52:47,434 --> 01:52:51,200
- (George) They'll have a playback?
- (man) That's the first time for them

1521
01:52:51,271 --> 01:52:54,331
- to hear the real thing.
- I hope they like it.

1522
01:52:54,407 --> 01:52:57,570
Because in the rehearsal room
we have commercial versions.

1523
01:52:57,644 --> 01:53:02,138
And even then they haven't heard it
like you and I have heard it.

1524
01:53:02,582 --> 01:53:04,846
We'll play you the opening of the show.

1525
01:53:04,918 --> 01:53:07,409
To explain what we've done
with the music is,

1526
01:53:07,487 --> 01:53:14,359
all of the music for the show is basically
chopped Beatles stuff from all their tapes

1527
01:53:14,427 --> 01:53:21,162
that my dad, who's here now,
recorded from 1962 to '69 onwards.

1528
01:53:21,234 --> 01:53:22,826
(cheering)

1529
01:53:24,904 --> 01:53:27,668
(George) We're embarking on
a new direction here.

1530
01:53:27,740 --> 01:53:32,006
The sounds we are getting are not
the sounds you would get in a studio.

1531
01:53:32,078 --> 01:53:34,069
It's a different thing altogether.

1532
01:53:34,147 --> 01:53:40,780
It's sounds that are designed to enhance
the visuals and make the show exciting.

1533
01:53:40,854 --> 01:53:43,982
("Get Back" starts up/audience cheers)

1534
01:53:44,057 --> 01:53:47,584
Jojo was a man
who thought he was a loner

1535
01:53:47,660 --> 01:53:50,993
But he knew it couldn't last

1536
01:53:51,631 --> 01:53:55,294
Jojo left his home
in Tucson, Arizona

1537
01:53:55,368 --> 01:53:58,030
For some California grass

1538
01:53:59,072 --> 01:54:00,835
Get back

1539
01:54:00,974 --> 01:54:02,771
Get back

1540
01:54:02,842 --> 01:54:06,278
Get back
to where you once belonged

1541
01:54:06,880 --> 01:54:08,313
Get back

1542
01:54:08,848 --> 01:54:10,679
Get back...

1543
01:54:10,750 --> 01:54:15,619
When I heard the show in Las Vegas
and heard the sound quality,

1544
01:54:15,688 --> 01:54:18,987
I was blown away,
'cause I'm listening and thinking,

1545
01:54:19,058 --> 01:54:22,425
"Wow, that snare drum!
I can't believe it!"

1546
01:54:22,495 --> 01:54:27,194
It's just so clear, it's so original.
You just don't hear snare drums like that.

1547
01:54:27,267 --> 01:54:30,168
("Glass Onion")

1548
01:54:31,871 --> 01:54:33,862
Oh, yeah

1549
01:54:35,608 --> 01:54:37,599
Oh, yeah

1550
01:54:39,612 --> 01:54:41,978
Oh, yeah!

1551
01:55:27,135 --> 01:55:31,731
("La Marseillaise" opening
of "All You Need Is Love")

1552
01:55:33,808 --> 01:55:37,209
(man) I remember clearly when
we decided with Dominic Champagne

1553
01:55:37,278 --> 01:55:39,769
to work in 360 degrees.

1554
01:55:39,847 --> 01:55:47,276
For me it was impossible to see the show
in an Italian way of seeing a show -

1555
01:55:47,355 --> 01:55:52,122
I mean, from being outside the frame
of the theater.

1556
01:55:52,794 --> 01:55:56,753
It's very difficult.
It's a nightmare to work like that.

1557
01:55:56,831 --> 01:56:01,825
For the light, for the video, for the stage,
for the artists, it's very, very tough.

1558
01:56:01,903 --> 01:56:05,703
All the exits of the stage
are inside the audience.

1559
01:56:05,773 --> 01:56:10,176
Also, even the video projections
are in the audience.

1560
01:56:10,244 --> 01:56:15,147
And it's very important because it means
the audience can have the feeling

1561
01:56:15,216 --> 01:56:19,915
that they are inside the show
and can live an experience.

1562
01:56:21,956 --> 01:56:24,584
(man #2) The challenge is
to use those screens

1563
01:56:24,659 --> 01:56:34,330
as something who places you not outside
of the scene, but inside the stage.

1564
01:56:36,070 --> 01:56:41,667
My approach is more working with
optical effect, natural effect.

1565
01:56:41,742 --> 01:56:46,441
It's always better
if I can shoot what I have to do,

1566
01:56:46,514 --> 01:56:51,975
and then, of course, I put filters,
I composite and everything.

1567
01:56:52,053 --> 01:57:02,952
But my first material, the roots are
always better if I do it like a handcrafter.

1568
01:57:03,030 --> 01:57:05,362
And I'm sure of that.

1569
01:57:05,433 --> 01:57:07,264
- It must be all right.
- OK, let's go.

1570
01:57:07,335 --> 01:57:09,235
- Don't, John.
- Sorry.

1571
01:57:11,305 --> 01:57:12,897
- (McCartney) OK?
- (Lennon) Yes.

1572
01:57:12,974 --> 01:57:14,805
(McCartney) Now!

1573
01:57:14,876 --> 01:57:18,107
- (Lennon) Yes, sir, that's my baby!
- (McCartney) Straight away.

1574
01:57:18,179 --> 01:57:20,374
- (Lennon) We'll do this again.
- OK. Go!

1575
01:57:20,448 --> 01:57:22,712
(Lennon) Sorry. I feel less than useless...

1576
01:57:22,783 --> 01:57:30,121
Apple Corps gave to Cirque all those
recording sessions between '63 and '69,

1577
01:57:30,191 --> 01:57:32,955
during which The Beatles
were recording their songs,

1578
01:57:33,027 --> 01:57:36,258
with which I could make a montage.

1579
01:57:38,232 --> 01:57:41,463
(McCartney) Are we still
recording even now?

1580
01:57:41,535 --> 01:57:46,302
(Lennon) No, I don't think so.
You're not being funny, are you?

1581
01:57:46,374 --> 01:57:51,539
- I can hear voices talking.
- (Ringo) Nobody was listening.

1582
01:57:51,612 --> 01:57:53,011
(moaning)

1583
01:57:53,080 --> 01:57:59,542
(Lennon) I get something in me head and
all the walls of Rome couldn't stop me.

1584
01:57:59,620 --> 01:58:07,220
They had a great sense of humor. That's
what I tried to show with this montage.

1585
01:58:07,295 --> 01:58:11,857
- (Lennon) Paul, it's very hard to sing this.
- (Ringo) Do I love you!

1586
01:58:11,933 --> 01:58:13,093
Ringo, stop!

1587
01:58:13,167 --> 01:58:19,072
Of course, I had to sign so many papers
to promise I won't sell it over the net!

1588
01:58:19,140 --> 01:58:24,373
But for a year and a half
it was such a terrific experience.

1589
01:58:24,445 --> 01:58:28,506
- Let's get this show on the road.
- (Lennon) OK, George. Go ahead.

1590
01:58:28,582 --> 01:58:33,747
This is the greatest band in the world
and you can hear them work together.

1591
01:58:33,821 --> 01:58:37,188
And it's clear as if it was now.

1592
01:58:40,795 --> 01:58:43,696
(man, in French)
I think their effect was universal.

1593
01:58:43,764 --> 01:58:48,633
Their arrival turned the world upside
down, seduced it and revolutionized it,

1594
01:58:48,703 --> 01:58:50,694
and it was the same everywhere.

1595
01:58:50,771 --> 01:58:52,796
("Revolution")

1596
01:58:58,813 --> 01:59:02,544
You say you want a revolution

1597
01:59:02,616 --> 01:59:04,709
Well, you know...

1598
01:59:04,785 --> 01:59:08,186
I started making costumes
at the age of eight.

1599
01:59:08,255 --> 01:59:11,349
I like to give the impression

1600
01:59:11,425 --> 01:59:15,156
that the character
comes from an unknown world

1601
01:59:15,229 --> 01:59:18,426
but, by the details in the costume,

1602
01:59:18,499 --> 01:59:21,730
by the manner in which
he or she moves,

1603
01:59:21,802 --> 01:59:25,898
give the impression that that world exists
and the character is a part of it.

1604
01:59:27,041 --> 01:59:31,137
(woman) So this is all costumes
from the presentation.

1605
01:59:31,212 --> 01:59:32,543
(applause)

1606
01:59:32,613 --> 01:59:36,105
There are references to
absolutely loads of names,

1607
01:59:36,183 --> 01:59:38,777
like Michelle, Polythene Pam,

1608
01:59:38,853 --> 01:59:42,812
Sugarplum Fairy,
Father McKenzie, Lady Madonna.

1609
01:59:42,890 --> 01:59:46,690
There's an entire universe,
an entire population of people, really,

1610
01:59:46,761 --> 01:59:51,721
who exist most probably in
the imaginations of thousands of people,

1611
01:59:51,799 --> 01:59:55,929
because there were thousands of people
worldwide who listened to The Beatles.

1612
01:59:56,003 --> 02:00:02,704
So we had an enormous responsibility in
portraying these characters in the show.

1613
02:00:02,777 --> 02:00:05,644
All the lonely people

1614
02:00:05,713 --> 02:00:08,705
Where do they all belong?

1615
02:00:10,151 --> 02:00:12,142
(woman) I have two favorite props.

1616
02:00:12,219 --> 02:00:17,213
The first one is Eleanor Rigby's train
because it's really made from junk parts.

1617
02:00:17,291 --> 02:00:23,628
So it's really made from antiques,
so it has a real life. It's not newly made.

1618
02:00:23,697 --> 02:00:25,528
This one carries a lot of...

1619
02:00:25,599 --> 02:00:29,296
I remember each part of this train,
where I buy it.

1620
02:00:29,370 --> 02:00:33,500
The other one is Sgt Pepper's bundle
'cause I think it's so...

1621
02:00:33,574 --> 02:00:37,340
Because it's a sphere, it's like
he's carrying the world on his back.

1622
02:00:37,411 --> 02:00:40,608
It's very poetic, I think, this image.

1623
02:00:41,615 --> 02:00:45,176
Dominic is a prop-consuming guy.

1624
02:00:45,252 --> 02:00:52,021
I heard in previous Cirque shows a lot of
things were sent to the Cirque warehouse.

1625
02:00:52,093 --> 02:00:58,259
But on this show, I think I have two or
three major props who were cut. That's it.

1626
02:00:58,332 --> 02:01:02,063
And there are more than 600 props
on this show.

1627
02:01:02,136 --> 02:01:05,435
And every day he's asking for more -
he's still asking for more.

1628
02:01:05,506 --> 02:01:10,205
I'll continue to feed him because I like
that my work is so integrated in this show.

1629
02:01:16,050 --> 02:01:19,042
Dominic is a guy
who puts a lot of stuff on stage.

1630
02:01:19,120 --> 02:01:25,582
We are both big hockey fans,
so we have a kind of a language.

1631
02:01:25,659 --> 02:01:29,288
We have one puck, OK?
So where's the puck now?

1632
02:01:29,363 --> 02:01:35,666
I have to put the audience
to help them to focus, to follow the story.

1633
02:01:35,736 --> 02:01:42,904
Sometimes we have two pucks, but we try
to keep the game at one puck on the ice!

1634
02:01:42,977 --> 02:01:45,537
But it's a big, big challenge.

1635
02:01:45,613 --> 02:01:50,141
And after that, I have to express myself
artistically, you know,

1636
02:01:50,217 --> 02:01:54,051
with colors, with emotion
in relation to the music,

1637
02:01:54,121 --> 02:01:58,148
with rhythm, with beat,
with counter beat,

1638
02:01:58,225 --> 02:02:01,319
with a big "Whoo!"

1639
02:02:01,395 --> 02:02:03,727
And I like to, you know...

1640
02:02:03,797 --> 02:02:07,563
"Lucy In The Sky",
it's a song that I like visually

1641
02:02:07,635 --> 02:02:10,001
because I put a lot of hours on that,

1642
02:02:10,070 --> 02:02:15,337
but with some other songs I'm more
laid-back and just install a nice ambiance.

1643
02:02:15,409 --> 02:02:19,812
That means that
we recreate a place, a space.

1644
02:02:19,880 --> 02:02:22,678
Woke up, got out of bed

1645
02:02:22,750 --> 02:02:26,083
Dragged a comb across my head...

1646
02:02:26,153 --> 02:02:29,316
Those tracks have been recorded
40 years ago,

1647
02:02:29,390 --> 02:02:34,589
and everything that I discover with
the lyrics and the way they were writing

1648
02:02:34,662 --> 02:02:36,892
and the sense of humor they had...

1649
02:02:36,964 --> 02:02:39,489
They were four guys, you know?

1650
02:02:39,567 --> 02:02:44,903
That's what I'd like people to remember
when they come and see the show.

1651
02:02:44,972 --> 02:02:47,463
("Glass Onion")

1652
02:02:48,842 --> 02:02:51,072
Oh, yeah

1653
02:02:52,980 --> 02:02:55,312
Oh, yeah...

1654
02:02:56,217 --> 02:03:00,449
(man) The first time I get inside
the Abbey Road Studio

1655
02:03:00,521 --> 02:03:06,619
I was thinking about all the archives
that I was supposed to check.

1656
02:03:07,027 --> 02:03:10,087
So many pictures.

1657
02:03:10,164 --> 02:03:16,660
I spent a week, ten hours a day,
watching The Beatles.

1658
02:03:16,737 --> 02:03:19,604
And finally, I had this flash.

1659
02:03:19,673 --> 02:03:26,909
I was like, "We don't want to be
documentary with our concept."

1660
02:03:26,981 --> 02:03:30,940
"We want to bring the people
inside their universe."

1661
02:03:31,018 --> 02:03:37,981
"So why don't we use all the pictures
to create one picture?"

1662
02:03:38,058 --> 02:03:40,049
Finally it's a little movie,

1663
02:03:40,127 --> 02:03:43,824
so you have thousands of movies
inside the image,

1664
02:03:43,897 --> 02:03:46,832
like a kaleidoscope of their life.

1665
02:03:46,900 --> 02:03:49,266
("All You Need Is Love")

1666
02:03:50,604 --> 02:03:53,368
(refrain) Love is all you need...

1667
